Let $a$ denote the price of a sack of apples, $b$ the price of a bunch of bananas, $c$ the price of a cantaloupe, and $d$ the price of a carton of dates. We can express the information given in the problem by the following system of linear equations:  \begin{align*}
a+b+c+d &= 20\\
2a &= d\\
a-b &= c
\end{align*}

Substituting into the first equation for $c$ and $d$ gives $a + b + a - b + 2a = 20$, which simplifies to $4a = 20$, so $a = 5$. From here, we use $a$ to find $d = 2 \cdot 5 = 10$. We put these values into the first equation to get $5 + b + c + 10 = 20$, so $b + c = \boxed{ \$ 5}$.

We can find this answer by plugging 5 into the function: \begin{align*} f(5)& = \dfrac{5+1}{3(5)-4}
\\ & = \dfrac{6}{15-4}
\\ & = \boxed{\dfrac{6}{11}}
\end{align*}

Let $p$ be the number of Popsicles Megan can finish in 4 hours and 30 minutes. If we convert that period of time into minutes, we find that 4 hours and 30 minutes is equal to $(4)(60)+30=270$ minutes. From here, we can set up the proportion  \begin{align*} \frac{x}{270}& =\frac{1}{15}
\\\Rightarrow \qquad x& =\left(\frac{1}{15}\right)(270)
\\\Rightarrow \qquad x& =\boxed{18}
\end{align*}

